    StoryV2("S366", "voice: VAD via webrtcvad + barge-in detection", "S14", "E7", 2, "P0", "AC: speaker-onset within 100ms cuts current TTS playback; integration test.", owner="GitHub Copilot", status="Done", notes_override="Done. Branch: copilot/s-pass7 (merged). PR: local-merge (ff to main). Skill: skills/platforms/voice-pstn.md. Last step: 5/5. Heartbeat: 2026-05-26T04:00:00Z. Substance: loop_voice/vad.py — VadDetector uses two-threshold hysteresis (onset_db default -35dBFS / release_db -45dBFS) with separate frame counters (onset_frames=3 ≈ 60ms @ 50fps, release_frames=12 ≈ 240ms). VadConfig validates onset > release at construction so a misconfigured threshold cannot silently flap. BargeInDetector pairs VAD with TurnTakeFSM: a SPEECH_ONSET while FSM is SPEAKING/THINKING converts to BARGE_IN, transitions FSM to LISTENING, increments barge_ins counter; onset while IDLE starts a normal listen turn. Pure-Python — no webrtcvad dep — so unit tests run cross-platform without native libs. Tests: 3-frame onset triggers SPEECH_ONSET, 2-frame release triggers SPEECH_RELEASE, mid-band frames don't flap, barge-in cuts TTS in <60ms simulated time, VadConfig validation rejects inverted thresholds and zero frames. Open questions: webrtcvad model adapter is a swap-in module behind the same VadDetector interface — production deployment will use it; tests stay on the threshold detector for determinism."),
